    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Tokens entitling the bearer to a portion of bread; usually minted from non-precious metals. Historically these have been issued at different times for various reasons: examples include bronze tokens issued in ancient Rome to citizens to exchange for 'panis civilis,' and in later times, tokens issued to the needy, for example on the occasion of a person's death, often nobility, at their requiem mass.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
